Import Data from Postgres DB

# Data Setup
pw <- {
  "password"
}
# loads the PostgreSQL driver
drv <- dbDriver("PostgreSQL")


# create connection
con <- dbConnect(drv, dbname = "racecounts",
                 host = "aws-postgres-db.c5udgz7ro8hq.us-west-2.rds.amazonaws.com", port = 5432,
                 user = "postgres", password = pw)
rm(pw)

# load RC view 
insur <- dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT * FROM arei_health_insurance_county_2017")



# close the connection
# dbDisconnect(con)
# dbUnloadDriver(drv)

Reference Cookbook for R

Most basic plot

## plot test
# Very basic bar graph
ggplot(data=insur, aes(x=county_name, y=latino_pct_uninsured )) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity")

# garbage

Try again

ggplot(data=insur, aes(x=county_name, y=latino_pct_uninsured )) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  coord_flip()  # add a function to flip the x-y coordinates

# better! but keep going

Keep goingâ€¦

Reorder counties from highest to lowest %

# re order the counties highest to lowest
ggplot(data=insur, aes(x = reorder(county_name, latino_pct_uninsured ), y = latino_pct_uninsured )) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  coord_flip()  

# better

Add color dimension

Also titles

# Add another dimension of the data
# color the bars by racecounts quadrant
ggplot(data=insur, aes(x = reorder(county_name, latino_pct_uninsured ), 
                      y = latino_pct_uninsured , fill = quadrant)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("green", "orange", "red", "yellow" ), na.value="gray")+
  coord_flip()  +
  labs(title = "Uninsured Latinos (%)",
       subtitle = "2013-2017 5-Year Estimates")

Add labels and experiment with themes

# experiment with themes! add bar labels!
ggplot(data=insur, aes(x = reorder(county_name, latino_pct_uninsured ), 
                      y = latino_pct_uninsured , fill = quadrant)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("green", "orange", "red", "yellow" ), na.value="gray")+
  coord_flip()  +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(round(latino_pct_uninsured, 0), "%")),  # assign the % homeowner attribute, round to 1 decimal place
            size=2.5,   # set font size 
            position = position_dodge(width = 1), vjust=0 , hjust=0) + # adjust alignment of labels
  labs(title = "Uninsured Latinos (%)",
       subtitle = "2013-2017 5-Year Estimates") +
  theme_tufte()

  # Type theme_ to get a preview of the themes available

Interactive Map

Spatial data

There are many ways to deal with spatial data in R.

The function pgGetGeom() allows us to import geometries from the Postgresql database with a WHERE clause:

# load libraries
library(leaflet)
library(sf)
library(rgdal)
library(rpostgis)
library(RColorBrewer)

# Get county geometries - query county boundaries from race counts database, query only CA
shp <- pgGetGeom(con, "cb_2017_us_county_500k", clauses = "where statefp = '06'")

# review data
head(shp@data)

Spatial data frames are slightly different animals in R. For example, to look at the data in a spatial df above, I called shp@data. We donâ€™t need to get into this too much now, just be aware.

Quick test plot of the shapefile

# quick test plot 
spplot(shp, "name")

# yes this looks like how we were expecting

Add data to spatial df

Use the merge() function to join a data frame to a spatial data, make sure the spatial data frame is listed first in the function in order to maintain data type = spatial.

# map data

# join in race counts data data 
insur_dat = merge(shp, insur, by.x="name", by.y="county_name", all=TRUE)

# review data -- first 16 columns

Interactive Map

# define color palette
 
 pal <- colorBin(
  palette = "YlOrRd",
  domain = insur_dat$latino_pct_uninsured, bins = 5,
  pretty = FALSE
)


# map
leaflet(insur_dat) %>%                                        # call leaflet library
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>%   # call basemap tiles from carto
  
  addPolygons(data=insur_dat, color="gray",          # define data and aesthetics to be mapped
              weight=1, fillOpacity = 0.7,
              fillColor = ~pal(latino_pct_uninsured), # fill color of the polygons, using RColorBrewer palette
            
        # define actions & style for when the user hovers over the polygon
              highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
                                    color = "white",         
                                    weight = 2, 
                                    bringToFront = TRUE),

        # define popup text -- concatenate data values with text labels
            popup = paste0(insur_dat$name, " County</br>",   
                       insur_dat$latino_pct_uninsured, 
                       "% Uninsured Latinx")) %>%
  
  # add legend
  addLegend(position = "bottomleft",
            pal = pal,                                  
            values = ~latino_pct_uninsured,
            title="Uninsured Latinos (%)" )

How to View and Share the Output of RMarkdown

  • RMarkdown can produce htmls, Word docs or PDFs.

  • HTML output is self-contained

    • Open file locally in browser (this file can be emailed to others and opened locally in their browser as well)

    • Create a Github page to host your html file

Github

  • Create a Github repository that is web page-enabled, then upload your file.

  • No html/css/web programming required, R & Github take care of all of that for you. Easy peasey!

Demo Rmarkdown to Github Workflow

  • Open markdown file Example_RMarkdown.Rmd

  • Knit

  • Open locally

  • Upload to Github Repo
